Filtration via membrane requires less space and is easy to operate [184]. It needs low energy to run, low transmembrane pressure, but the presence of NOM pollutes the membrane thus limiting its wide application in wastewater treatment. Research demonstrates the pollution of CNTs/polyethersulfone (C/P) membranes by natural water compared to pure polyethersulfone membranes. The C/P is a hybrid membrane of organic and inorganic material and might be served as a future precursor for new membrane production [184]. It is expected that these membranes would possess properties to build membranes from polymeric substances such as CNTs and are very stable physiochemically [188]. Inorganic molecules composite membranes of nanosize display significant properties i.e. strong hydrophilicity, huge permeation selectivity, and better fouling control [28,184]. The schematic illustration of normal membrane separation method and adapted CNTs composite membrane are shown in Fig. 11
                            [187]. Electrochemically changed membrane filters interrupt the contaminants and can be used to reduce organic pollution and deactivate viruses and bacteria (Fig. 11b) [187]. An organic-CNT membrane is beneficial owing to its CNT’s fibrous structure, large phase proportion, high surface area, and advanced structure containing mesopore. These properties can be used for membrane fouling control, large adsorption ability, and less equilibrium time compared to other carbonaceous materials [182,184]. The C/P combined membrane show less flux deterioration (about 42%) than pure Polyethersulfone (PES) membranes during surface water infiltration containing NOM [184]. This might be owing to much hydrophilic C/P nature relative to hydrophobic character (PES membrane). The C/P blended CNT membrane composed of functionalized MWCNTs deal with NO3 and H2SO4 results in the formation of carboxylic (-COOH) group. The presence of (-COOH) enhances MWCNTs hydrophilicity (Fig. 12
                           ) [39,184]. Researches have displayed that C/Pcombined membrane holding 0.5% MWCNTs shows minimum flux decline in surface water filtration owing to better phase separation among CNT and polyethersulfone because bigger pore sizes suggest high flux. Conversely, C/P blends enclosing a larger MWCNTs percentage displayed a decrease in flux [184]. The NOM rejection among virgin PES and 0.5% C/P blended membranes was statistically same while 2% C/P blend had a foulant total amount (NOM) less than thrice relative to virgin PES membranes. A layer of foulant is generated even with a C/P blend high (NOM) rejection rate. To remove this foulant layer caustic and oxidizing agent may be used during backwashing. Hydrophilic membrane flux recovery is much efficient than hydrophobic is steady through ease and difficulty in eliminating foulant layer off the C/P blended and virgin PES membranes, respectively [189]. Organic/inorganic hybrid membrane e.g. CNT-blended membranes controls foulant and (NOM) rejection consequently can improve these problems successfully affect the membrane technology use in water treatment [182,184].
